It=E2=80=99s easy to dunk on Red One, the early-Christmas-season film about=
 a North Pole security officer (Dwayne Johnson) recruiting a mercenary (Chr=
is Evans) to help track down a kidnapped and uncomfortably buff Santa Claus=
 (J.K. Simmons). The Amazon MGM Studios action-comedy cost a reported $253 =
million to produce, not including P&A. Its Friday-Sunday debut netted $32 m=
illion, while the film earned just $50 million in two weeks of overseas the=
atrical release. By most conventional theatrical measures, this is a catast=
rophe.

But the true verdict on the film is slightly more nuanced. Red One actually=
 notched a solid opening for an original theatrical release, in line with o=
ther moderate successes from the past four years like The Lost City, Free G=
uy, and If. It also opened in
line with other Rock vehicles, such as the $36 million launches of Central =
Intelligence, Jumanji: Welcome to the Jungle, and Rampage. However, all of =
the aforementioned cost closer to $100 million than $200 million to produce=
=2E

Also, with an A=E2=80=93 from CinemaScore and a surprisingly robust 2.93x F=
riday-to-weekend multiplier, Red One might yet enjoy the longer-tail succes=
s of other Christmas-themed movies released before Thanksgiving. If Red One=
 performs like The Santa Clause 2 ($129 million after a $29 million debut i=
n 2006), it could end up with around $142 million in North America. Meanwhi=
le, Red One is looking at an overseas total=E2=80=94courtesy of distributor=
-for-hire Warner Bros.=E2=80=94of around $90 million. So, if you add in the=
 international gross, the catastrophe may be downgraded to mid-range disast=
er before it eventually heads over to Prime Video.

