The Hybrid Model

But we can=E2=80=99t give Red One too much of a pass. It=E2=80=99s still a =
$250 million movie released in a theatrical environment where even a $100 m=
illion-budgeted original is considered a major roll of the dice. Yes, the f=
ilm was greenlit and budgeted for streaming before Amazon acquired MGM, and=
 the theatrical release was ultimately considered additive to its economics=
=2E And, yes, $125 million domestic is=20=
considered a solid run for a live-acti=
on original in the current ecosystem. At the end of the day, Red One is lik=
ely to surpass the global grosses of recent Apple TV+ originals like Killer=
s of the Flower Moon ($158 million) and Argylle ($96 million), as well as f=
ilms that were initially intended for HBO Max, like Blue Beetle ($131 milli=
on).

Ironically, a $125 million=E2=80=93$150 million domestic finish might
have been an unvarnished domestic win for MGM, even with soft overseas numb=
ers, had production costs been on par with the Johnson=E2=80=99s successful=
 2010s vehicles. During his peak butts-in-seats era, the $80 million=E2=80=
=93$130 million-budgeted movies=E2=80=94Journey 2: The Mysterious Island, S=
an Andreas, or Rampage=E2=80=94were massive hits, with $350 million=E2=80=
=93$475 million global cumes. So, why did Red One cost $253 million? Well, =
partly because the film was budgeted for streaming, meaning A-level talent =
got fatter paychecks upfront in lieu of performance-based box office bonuse=
s. While it may be unfair to punish Amazon for a streaming-intended release=
 not living up to a theatrical revenue-based profitability model, it=E2=80=
=99s also the pool they chose to swim in.

The Rock Hits the Ceiling

Red One is just the latest example of the industry overestimating Johnson=
=E2=80=99s bankability. Folks will show up for him to a point, but his appe=
al is limited unless it=E2=80=99s a Fast Saga sequel or a film becomes an u=
nto-itself sensation like Sony=E2=80=99s Jumanji sequels. And that limit, o=
f course, should be reflected in the cost. Neither the $90 million Jumanji:=
 Welcome to the Jungle nor the $120 million Jumanji: The Next Level was so =
expensive to produce that their respective $962 million and $800 million wo=
rldwide cumes were required to turn a profit. And the fact that Red One was=
 made for Amazon only made it more expensive, given Johnson=E2=80=99s rumor=
ed $50 million-plus buyout.

Maybe the critical lesson going forward=E2=80=94beyond the fact that Dwayne=
 Johnson should make movies that can be theatrical
successes with even $350 million in worldwide receipts=E2=80=94is that stre=
aming originals should be budgeted like theatrical originals when they debu=
t in theaters. That often means less money for talent upfront and more mone=
y spent on the movie itself. Netflix has already hinted at this change. And=
 it does seem distasteful for streamers that willingly overpaid for A-level=
 talent to try and make the couch competitive with theatrical stadium seati=
ng to then return to the old rules after changing the game. But, as demonst=
rated by Beetlejuice Beetlejuice (which went from a $147 million streaming =
title to a $100 million theatrical blockbuster that grossed $451 million wo=
rldwide), sometimes old school is the better school.

Nonetheless, all the caveats, disclaimers, and asterisks aside, Red One is =
still a $250 million movie that typifies a pattern of trying to turn almost=
 any marquee character or brand into a franchise-friendly action-fantasy mo=
vie. This idea
makes no more commercial sense in 2024 than it did in 1985 with Santa Claus=
: The Movie or 2013 with Jack the Giant Slayer. It=E2=80=99s one thing to o=
ffer the benefit of the doubt to the kind of non-franchise, star-driven, ad=
ult-skewing genre film that Hollywood used to make before I.P. took over. I=
t=E2=80=99s another to bend over backward when tech companies and alleged d=
isruptors make the same mistakes as their Hollywood rivals.

