          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">It=E2=80=99s easy t=
o dunk on <i>Red One</i>, the early-Christmas-season film about a North Pol=
e security officer (<b>Dwayne Johnson</b>) recruiting a mercenary (<b>Chris=
 Evans</b>) to help track down a kidnapped and uncomfortably buff Santa Cla=
us (<b>J.K. Simmons</b>). The Amazon MGM Studios action-comedy cost a repor=
ted <i>$253 million</i> to produce, not including P&amp;A. Its Friday-Sunda=
y debut netted $32 million, while the film earned just $50 million in two w=
eeks of overseas theatrical release. By most conventional theatrical measur=
es, this is a catastrophe.<br/><br/>But the true verdict on the film is <i>=
slightly </i>more nuanced. <i>Red One </i>actually notched a solid opening =
for an original theatrical release, in line with other moderate successes f=
rom the past four years like <i>The Lost City</i>,<i> Free Guy</i>, and <i>=
If</i>. It also opened in
line with other Rock vehicles, such as the $36 million launches of <i>Centr=
al Intelligence</i>, <i>Jumanji: Welcome to the Jungle</i>, and <i>Rampage<=
/i>. However, all of the aforementioned cost closer to $100 million than $2=
00 million to produce.<br/><br/>Also, with an A=E2=80=93 from CinemaScore a=
nd a surprisingly robust 2.93x Friday-to-weekend multiplier, <i>Red One</i>=
 might yet enjoy the longer-tail success of other Christmas-themed movies r=
eleased before Thanksgiving. If <i>Red One </i>performs like <i>The Santa C=
lause 2 </i>($129 million after a $29 million debut in 2006), it could end =
up with around $142 million in North America. Meanwhile, <i>Red One </i>is =
looking at an overseas total=E2=80=94courtesy of distributor-for-hire Warne=
r Bros.=E2=80=94of around $90 million. So, if you add in the international =
gross, the catastrophe may be downgraded to mid-range disaster before it ev=
entually heads over to Prime Video.<br/></td>
