          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">But we can=E2=80=99=
t give <i>Red One </i>too much of a pass. It=E2=80=99s still a $250 million=
 movie released in a theatrical environment where even a $100 million-budge=
ted original is considered a major roll of the dice. Yes, the film was gree=
nlit and budgeted for streaming before Amazon acquired MGM, and the theatri=
cal release was ultimately considered additive to its economics. And, <i>ye=
s</i>, $125 million domestic is considered a solid run for a live-action or=
iginal in the current ecosystem. At the end of the day, <i>Red One </i>is l=
ikely to surpass the global grosses of recent Apple TV+ originals like <i>K=
illers of the Flower Moon </i>($158 million) and <i>Argylle </i>($96 millio=
n), as well as films that were initially intended for HBO Max, like <i>Blue=
 Beetle </i>($131 million). <br/><br/>Ironically, a $125 million=E2=80=93$1=
50 million domestic finish might
have been an unvarnished domestic win for MGM, even with soft overseas numb=
ers, had production costs been on par with the Johnson=E2=80=99s successful=
 2010s vehicles. During his peak butts-in-seats era, the $80 million=E2=80=
=93$130 million-budgeted movies=E2=80=94<i>Journey 2: The Mysterious Island=
</i>, <i>San Andreas</i>, or <i>Rampage=E2=80=94</i>were massive hits, with=
 $350 million=E2=80=93$475 million global cumes. So, why did <i>Red One</i>=
 cost $253 million? Well, partly because the film was budgeted for streamin=
g, meaning A-level talent got fatter paychecks upfront in lieu of performan=
ce-based box office bonuses. While it may be unfair to punish Amazon for a =
streaming-intended release not living up to a theatrical revenue-based prof=
itability model, it=E2=80=99s also the pool they chose to swim in. <br/></t=
