          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><i>Red One</i> is j=
ust the latest example of the industry overestimating Johnson=E2=80=99s ban=
kability. Folks will show up for him to a point, but his appeal is limited =
unless it=E2=80=99s a <i>Fast Saga</i> sequel or a film becomes an unto-its=
elf sensation like Sony=E2=80=99s <i>Jumanji </i>sequels. And that limit, o=
f course, should be reflected in the cost. Neither the $90 million <i>Juman=
ji: Welcome to the Jungle </i>nor the $120 million <i>Jumanji: The Next Lev=
el </i>was so expensive to produce that their respective $962 million and $=
800 million worldwide cumes were <i>required</i> to turn a profit. And the =
fact that <i>Red One</i> was made for Amazon only made it more expensive, g=
iven Johnson=E2=80=99s rumored $50 million-plus buyout.<br/><br/>Maybe the =
critical lesson going forward=E2=80=94beyond the fact that Dwayne Johnson s=
hould make movies that can be theatrical
successes with even $350 million in worldwide receipts=E2=80=94is that stre=
aming originals should be budgeted like theatrical originals when they debu=
t in theaters. That often means less money for talent upfront and more mone=
y spent on the movie itself. Netflix has already hinted at this change. And=
 it does seem distasteful for streamers that willingly overpaid for A-level=
 talent to try and make the couch competitive with theatrical stadium seati=
ng to then return to the old rules after changing the game. But, as demonst=
rated by <i>Beetlejuice Beetlejuice </i>(which went from a $147 million str=
eaming title to a $100 million theatrical blockbuster that grossed $451 mil=
lion worldwide), sometimes old school is the better school.<br/><br/>Noneth=
eless, all the caveats, disclaimers, and asterisks aside, <i>Red One </i>is=
 still a $250 million movie that typifies a pattern of trying to turn almos=
t any marquee character or brand into a franchise-friendly action-fantasy m=
ovie. This idea
makes no more commercial sense in 2024 than it did in 1985 with <i>Santa Cl=
aus: The Movie </i>or 2013 with <i>Jack the Giant Slayer</i>. It=E2=80=99s =
one thing to offer the benefit of the doubt to the kind of non-franchise, s=
tar-driven, adult-skewing genre film that Hollywood used to make before I.P=
=2E took over. It=E2=80=99s another to ben=
d over backward when tech companies=
 and alleged disruptors make the same mistakes as their Hollywood rivals. <=
br/></td>
