x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><i>My Thursday anal=
ysis of Disney=E2=80=99s bullish guidance in streaming attracted a few cont=
rarian takes. Some examples=E2=80=A6</i><br/> <br/>=E2=80=9CYour newsletter=
 seems to be calling this as the moment that Disney=E2=80=99s steaming has =
turned the corner. Maybe. But I=E2=80=99d only note that their entertainmen=
t D.T.C. profit margin is in the low single digits, and their direct-to-con=
sumer business is still $11 billion-plus in the red, not including the bill=
ions more they might be on the hook for once the haggling over the final va=
lue of Hulu is worked out. In other words, streaming is a long way from bei=
ng a consistently good business for Disney. Might be someday, but Netflix h=
as a huge head start and Disney has been running with sandbags since the be=
ginning. It=E2=80=99s really only a good business for Netflix so far.=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=94<i>A journalist</i><br/> <br/>=EF=BB=BF=E2=80=9CNot sure if
it=E2=80=99s fair to say the right streaming strategy is =E2=80=98more mode=
st, narrowly tailored content investment, aggressive windowing, and third-p=
arty licensing=E2=80=99 when the most profitable streamer does the exact op=
posite of all those things.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94<i>An executive</i><br/> <br/=
>=E2=80=9COne of the issues with Disney financials is that it=E2=80=99s mas=
king a shit ton of streaming costs in its TV business=E2=80=94all Disney Ch=
annel/Disney Junior production and localization budgets, for example. Easy =
to post streaming profits in this scenario=E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94<i>An=
other executive</i><br/> <br/>=E2=80=9CSo everyone but Netflix and Disney a=
re screwed?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94<i>Yet another executive</i><br/></td>
